{{ill|Tottori Gokoku Shrine|WD=Q135476768|simple|ja|鳥取県護国神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tottori Gokoku Shrine|WD=Q135476768|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (鳥取県護国神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|WD=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|Japan|en|Japan|WD=Q17|lt=Japan}}.  It is a [[Gokoku Shrines|Gokoku Shrine]], or a shrine dedicated to war dead.{{Efn|Is this [[WP:BLUE]] considering that the shrine is literally named as such?}} Such shrines were made to serve to enshrine the war dead, and they were all considered "branches" of {{ill|Yasukuni Shrine|en|Yasukuni Shrine|WD=Q242803|lt=Yasukuni Shrine}}. They were renamed from {{ill|Shōkonsha|en|Shōkonsha|WD=Q11497810|lt=Shokonsha}} in 1939.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=TAKAYAMA |first=K. PETER |date=1990 |title=Enshrinement and Persistency of Japanese Religion |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/23917081 |journal=Journal of Church and State |volume=32 |issue=3 |pages=527–547 |issn=0021-969X}}</ref>

Tottori Prefecture Gokoku Shrine is a Shinto shrine located in Tottori City, Tottori Prefecture, Japan. Gokoku shrines, known as "護国神社" (Gokoku Jinja) in Japanese, are dedicated to honoring the spirits of those who died in wars, serving as places of reverence and reflection.<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gokoku_Shrines</ref> 

Situated near the famous Tottori Sand Dunes, the shrine offers visitors a serene environment complemented by traditional Shinto architecture. The proximity to the sand dunes provides a unique backdrop, enhancing the shrine's tranquil atmosphere. <ref name=":0">https://www.thatch.co/guide/3zsvpgwt1ywz/view</ref>

Visitors to the shrine can explore its peaceful grounds, which are surrounded by lush greenery, making it an ideal spot for reflection or a quiet stroll. The beautiful torii gates and tranquil paths offer picturesque settings for photography enthusiasts. <ref>https://wanderlog.com/view/ovsavlnoml/tottoris-anime-towns--sand-dunes-guide</ref>

For those interested in Japanese history and culture, Tottori Prefecture Gokoku Shrine provides insight into the nation's efforts to honor and remember those who have served. Its location near other attractions, such as the Tottori Sand Dunes, makes it a worthwhile addition to any travel itinerary in the region. <ref name=":0" />

The shrine is located at Hamasaka, 1318-53, Tottori, Tottori 680-0001, Japan. For more information, visitors can contact the shrine at +81 857-22-4428. <ref>https://zaubee.com/biz/tottori-prefecture-gokoku-shrine-1mav63ez</ref>
